u seem to want <br />to just hide the thing under a rug - and _encouraging_ people to not even <br />try to work with a new and more flexible model.<br /><br />For example, there's nothing wrong with having people replace their <br />firmware when they want to. Equally, there's nothing wrong in having <br />distros put stable firmware into another package, so that you don't need <br />to have &lt;n&gt; different versions of the firmware in &lt;n&gt; different kernel <br />module directories just because you have &lt;n&gt; different versions of the <br />module itself.<br /><br />So why do you want to work so hard at not just encouraging people to get <br />the firmware loaded dynamically from the filesystem?<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
